{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508351"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2736"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583388"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:15:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:15:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2736"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2736"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.11,0.23,0.17,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78816"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2736"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64165"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78816"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents for review after being newly diagnosed with Parkinson\u0027s Disease two weeks ago. She reports improved movement with the commencement of levodopa/carbidopa, but has been experiencing nausea since this time. Her history includes hypercholesterolaemia and polycystic ovarian syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following anti-emetics is the most appropriate choice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Domperidone","Prochlorperazine","Metoclopramide","Promethazine","Dexamethasone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENausea is a common side-effect for those on anti-Parkinsonian medications, typically resulting from the conversion of levodopa to dopamine which stimulates the dopamine receptors in the area postrema (\u0027vomiting centre\u0027) in the brainstem, a structure which lies outside the blood-brain barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nausea can be minimised by introducing levodopa as a low dose, taking it with food and giving it in combination with a peripheral dopa decarboxylase inhibitor such as carbidopa or benserazide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDomperidone\u003C/strong\u003E is the safest choice of anti-emetic in Parkinson\u0027s disease. It selectively acts on peripheral D2 receptors to increase gastric motility, but importantly \u003Cem\u003Edoes not cross the blood-brain barrier (BBB)\u003C/em\u003E. Of note, it should be avoided in patients with a prolonged QT interval evident on ECG, as there is risk of serious cardiac events. The dose should be reduced in renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoclopramide, promethazine\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprochlorperazine \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be avoided in patients with Parkinson\u0027s Disease as they \u003Cem\u003Edo\u003C/em\u003E cross the blood-brain barrier, with dopamine (D2) receptor antagonism occurring at both central and peripheral receptors. This significantly increases risk of extra-pyramidal side effects (EPSE\u0027s) and worsening of her Parkinsonism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective anti-emetic as a stat dose, often used in post-operative settings. However, it is not ideal for long term use given its potential side effects including weight gain and immunosuppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther reasonable anti-emetics to consider for short term use include \u003Cstrong\u003Eondansetron\u003C/strong\u003E, although this can cause constipation, or \u003Cstrong\u003Ecyclizine\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Domperidone is the anti-emetic of choice in Parkinson\u0027s Disease.","Metoclopramide acts at both peripheral and central dopaminergic receptors, and can induce EPSEs in Parkinson\u0027s Disease.","Anti-emetics that cross the blood-brain barrier can worsen Parkinsonian symptoms."],"references":["Nawaz M, Close O. Considerations for the inpatient management of Parkinson\u2019s disease. The Pharmaceutical Journal [Internet]. 2020 [cited 12/08/21], Vol 304, No 7935;304(7935):DOI:10.1211/PJ.2020.20207802 Available from: https://pharmaceutical-journal.com/article/ld/considerations-for-the-inpatient-management-of-parkinsons-disease","Fung V, Hely M, Moore GD, Morris J. Drugs for Parkinson\u0027s disease. Aust Prescr 2001;24:92-5. https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2001.099 Available from: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/drugs-for-parkinsons-disease.html","Puoti MG, Assa A, Benninga M, Broekaert IJ, Carpi FJM, Deganello Saccomani M, Dolinsek J, Homan M, Mas E, Miele E, Tzivinikos C, Thomson M, Borrelli O. Drugs in Focus: Domperidone. J Pediatr Gastroenterol Nutr. 2023 Aug 1;77(2):e13-e22. doi: 10.1097/MPG.0000000000003822. Epub 2023 May 9. PMID: 37159421. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37159421/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64165"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2736"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64165"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T19:35:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T19:36:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2736"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78816"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"grou